commText: B0$ We already thought about it, the ball was gripping so we just wanted to stick it out. They miss their lengths and we could swing it around. Needing 30 off the final two, it was very gettable. I flicked one into the stands without really swinging at it. And that six over point put the icing on the cake. I wanted to finish the game off, but we have a finisher this year in Rinku. (On Rinku) He had told me what if the ball beats you, should we go for the run? I said for sure, I have faith in him to finish it last ball. I get goosebumps seeing him doing what he's been doing. I have company at the back end, he soaks the pressure off and he's been here for years now, a really hard-working guy. He's very funny outside the field, I try to stay as close to him while we are training. Feeling good, now!!

commText: B0$ When I was batting, I wanted to hold one end. Venky had a problem with his ankle so we were trying to get one big over here and there. 10 matches have gone, we were all waiting for that one Russell innings to come. He was one innings away, I kept backing him saying you have done a lot, and you will 100% win us a game. This pitch was a feel of home advantage as well. Our bowlers bowled badly at the death, I was angry that we conceded that many because this was a 160-165 run wicket. (On Rinku) I just keep telling him, believe in yourself because what you have achieved is something not many people ever will. When he was batting, the whole crowd was chanting 'Rinku, Rinku'. That is what he has earned this year. I've been at this franchise for many years now, I'm used to the Eden crowd screaming 'Russell, Russell' but to hear them shout 'Rinku, Rinku' makes me feel very happy and proud. That's the respect he has earned this season.

I0$ A thriller at the Eden Gardens goes the way of the hosts, but they were really made to sweat today, and got through thanks to some fantastic hitting by Dre Russ and some ordinary captaincy by Shikhar. With 180 to be chased down, KKR needed an explosive start but Rishi Dhawan and Nathan Ellis kept things quiet early on, with the latter picking up Gurbaz. Jason Roy sizzled and was taking the game away at one stage, but he holed out against Harpreet Brar. Skipper Nitish Rana hung in and scored a sketchy fifty, as the wicket become difficult to bat on with the spinners operating. KKR still had a lot to be done, needing 51 off the last four overs. But then Dhawan decided to bowl out his best bowler in Ellis, and simultaneously Russell took on the attack. He got a 15 run over off Ellis, and then smoked Sam Curran for three sixes in the penultimate over. The equation was down to 6 off the last over, and Arshdeep did well to take it till the last ball. But he erred with the yorker in the end and Rinku flicked it behind square for four!! That win takes KKR to 5th spot, PBKS enter must win territory from here...

commText: B0$ Kolkata Knight Riders have had a topsy-turvy season so far and hence, they find themselves in a must-win scenario. Another slip-up can literally ring the death knell for them. Sometimes, a crisis situation can bring out the best in you. The situation demands KKR to fire on all cylinders. On the other hand, Punjab Kings find themselves in a tricky situation. A loss tonight will push them into the must-win territory but a win will propel them into the third position – such has been the level of contests this season that nothing can be considered safe. Hello and a warm welcome to our live coverage of Match 53. When the going gets tough, the tough get going. Coming out triumphant in the face of adversity can bring a different kind of self-belief and both teams will be vying for that. The Eden surface has played true to its nature and both teams have the firepower in batting to capitalize on it. Can KKR break their 3-match losing streak at home? Or will PBKS outfox the hosts tonight? Stay with us as toss and team lineups are around the corner...

B0$ by B1$  
  
In his autobiography, AB de Villiers had described Eden Gardens as "an impressive stadium where the playing experience can be spoiled by a dead wicket and a rock-hard outfield." That was written back in 2016, ironically the same year that saw the pitches at the venue relaid. Cut forward to 2023 and Eden Gardens is the fastest scoring ground in IPL this season, with an average first innings score upwards of 211. While that might please de Villiers and the T20 fandom in general, what it's done is pare back the traditional strengths of Kolkata Knight Riders.  
  
KKR have lost three of their four home games this season. The last three have been on the bounce. While it's true that most other teams haven't had a happy homecoming after the pandemic outage and the hard reset of a mega auction, KKR's losses stand out in a way. Their losses at home have come despite the success of the spinners, their conventional power muscle that's held up again and been the most successful this season. But unlike other years, it hasn't quite translated into victories at home.  
  
Come Monday evening, KKR will have to contend with a team that's been harvesting big totals of late. Punjab Kings now have four consecutive scores in excess of 200, a record in IPL, and will be looking forward to making that five against a side that's clearly tentative at home and hasn't quite had its pacers level up in the tournament yet. But that said, what's also true is that PBKS have conceded 200+ totals in their last four matches and KKR will know that if this must-win encounter boils down to a batting skirmish, they have the firepower to match.

B4$ Pitch #4 has been readied for the fixture and this will be the third IPL match to be played on the strip this season. What's to note is that this pitch hasn't been watered as much as the previous tracks seen at the venue, largely due to "unreliable weather forecast" according to people in the know, and that could mean that a slightly drier track could be on offer. That will unwittingly play to KKR's spin strengths.  
  
As for dimensions, this pitch isn't bang in the center of the square and the bowlers operating from the pavilion end will have the longer part of the ground to their right. The curator said that there hasn't been much dew lately in Kolkata and he expects more of the same on game night too.
